    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_return",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Return Values",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "So far, our functions have printed results. But often you want a function to **calculate** something and give the result back so you can use it later."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `return` statement sends a value back from a function."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "using_return",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Using return",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Use the `return` keyword followed by the value you want to send back."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "def add_numbers(a, b):\n    result = a + b\n    return result\n\ntotal = add_numbers(5, 3)\nprint(total)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "8"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The function `add_numbers` adds numbers `5` and `3` and returns the result `8`, which is stored in the variable `total`."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "capturing_return",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can capture the returned value in a variable or use it directly."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "def multiply(x, y):\n    return x * y\n\n# Capture in variable\nanswer = multiply(4, 5)\nprint(answer)\n\n# Use directly\nprint(multiply(3, 7))",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "20\n21"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Both ways work - you can store the result or use it immediately."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
